Goal: Implement JWT-based user authentication.
North Star: Secure user access with minimal friction and no schema churn.

Constraints:
- Do NOT implement password reset in this scope.
- Do NOT modify existing users table schema.
- Do NOT store secrets in source control.

Phases:
1. Audit existing auth patterns and middleware wiring.
2. RED: write failing tests for login handler (valid creds, invalid creds, missing fields, locked user, token TTL claim).
3. GREEN: implement login + verifyToken middleware minimally.
4. RED: tests for logout + refresh-token edge cases.
5. GREEN: implement logout (revoke) + refresh.
6. REFACTOR: extract AuthService (SRP); inject tokenProvider (DIP); keep controllers thin.
7. Docs: JSDoc @param/@returns for AuthService and middleware; README section for configuration.

```ts
/**
 * Authenticates a user and returns a signed JWT.
 * @param creds email + password
 * @returns token string
 * @throws InvalidCredentialsError on bad email/password
 */
export class AuthService {
  constructor(private readonly users: UserRepo, private readonly tokens: TokenProvider) {}
  async login(creds: { email: string; password: string }): Promise<string> {
    if (!creds?.email || !creds?.password) throw new InvalidCredentialsError();
    const user = await this.users.findByEmail(creds.email);
    if (!user) throw new InvalidCredentialsError();
    const ok = await this.users.verifyPassword(user, creds.password);
    if (!ok) throw new InvalidCredentialsError();
    return this.tokens.sign({ sub: user.id });
  }
}
```

SOLID: SRP (AuthService only authenticates), OCP (swap TokenProvider), DIP (depend on interfaces). Edge cases: empty input, unknown user, timing attacks (use constant-time compare), expired tokens, clock skew.

